S'{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2014}}\n{{Infobox congressman\n|birthname     = Bruce Eugene Westerman\n|name          = Bruce Westerman\n|image         = WestermanOfficial.jpg\n|state         = [[Arkansas]]\n| office      = Member-elect of the<br>[[U.S. House of Representatives]]<br>from [[Arkansas\'s 4th congressional district|Arkansas\'s 4th district]] \n|term_start    = January 3, 2015\n|term_end      = \n| succeeding  = [[Tom Cotton]]\n| succeeded     = \n| state_house2=Arkansas\n| district2   =30th\n| term_start2 =January 2011\n| term_end2=January 2013 \n| preceded2=[[Bill Sample|William H. "Bill" Sample]]\n| succeeded2=Charles Armstrong\n| state_house3=Arkansas\n| district3=22nd\n| term_start3=January 2013\n| term_end3=January 2015\n| preceded3=[[Nate Bell]]\n| succeeded3=\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1967|11|18}}\n|birth_place =[[Hot Springs, Arkansas|Hot Springs]], [[Garland County, Arkansas|Garland County]]<br>[[Arkansas]], USA \n|death_date  = \n|death_place = \n|resting_place=\n|party       = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse      = Sharon Kay French Westerman\n|children    = Eli, Amie, Ethan, and Asa Westerman\n|alma_mater  = [[Fountain Lake High School]]<br>[[University of Arkansas]]<br>[[Yale University]]\n|occupation =[[Engineer]] and [[Forestry|forester]]\n|religion    = [[Southern Baptist]]\n}}\n\'\'\'Bruce Eugene Westerman\'\'\' (born November 18, 1967) is an [[engineer]] and [[Forestry|forester]] in his native [[Hot Springs, Arkansas|Hot Springs]], [[Arkansas]], who is the [[Majority Leader]] of the [[Arkansas House of Representatives]], in which he is serving his second and final two-year term. Westerman instead is the incoming  [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] member of the [[United States House of Representatives]] for [[Arkansas\'s 4th congressional district]]. The position opened when incumbent freshman Republican [[Tom Cotton]] ran, successfully as it developed, against  [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] [[U.S. Senator]] [[Mark Pryor]]. \n\n==Early life and education==\nWesterman graduated as [[valedictorian]] of [[Fountain Lake High School]] in Hot Springs. He attended the [[University of Arkansas]] in [[Fayetteville, Arkansas|Fayetteville]], where he played [[college football]] for the [[Arkansas Razorbacks football]] team. He graduated from UA with a [[Bachelor of Science]] in engineering in 1990 and subsequently received a [[master\'s degree]] in forestry from [[Yale University]] in [[New Haven, Connecticut|New Haven]], [[Connecticut]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/candidate/119120/bruce-westerman|title=Bruce Westerman\'s Biography|publisher=votesmart.org|accessdate=January 12, 2014}}</ref> \n\nWesterman is an engineer and forester with Mid-South Engineering Company. He served as president of the Arkansas chapter of the [[American Society of Agricultural and Biological Engineers|American Society of Agricultural and Biological Engineering]]. He is also a former chair of the Arkansas Academy of Biological and Agricultural Engineers. Westerman formerly served on the [[school board]] of the [[Fountain Lake School District]].\n\n==Arkansas House of Representatives==\n===Elections===\nHe ran for the [[Arkansas House of Representatives]] in 2010 without opposition to succeed fellow Republican [[Bill Sample]], who was instead elected to the [[Arkansas State Senate]].<ref>Westerman plans to run for Sample\'s seat in House. \'\'Hot Springs Village Voice\'\'. September 30, 2009</ref><ref>Westerman to resign from Fountain Lake school board. \'\'Hot Springs Village Voice\'\'. March 24, 2010</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sos.arkansas.gov/electionresults/index.php?ac:show:contest_statewide=1&elecid=231&contestid=122|title=State Representative District 030 - Certified, 2010|publisher=sos.arkansas.gov|accessdate=January 10, 2014}}</ref>\n\nWith the 2012 election, Westerman was transferred to his current District 22, in which he also ran without opposition in both the Republican primary and the [[general election]]. The incumbent District 22 lawmaker, Republican [[Nate Bell]] of [[Polk County, Arkansas|Polk County]] was switched to District 20.   \n\n===Tenure===\nWesterman served as the House Minority Leader in 2012 and House Majority Leader in 2013.<ref>http://www.arkansashouse.org/member/296/bruce-westerman</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Representative Westerman co-sponsored the amending of [[state income tax]] rates and supported the proposed spending cap on the state budget, but the latter measure failed by a two-vote margin in the House. He joined the majority to [[Veto override|override]] the [[veto]]es of Democratic [[governor of Arkansas|Governor]] [[Mike Beebe]] to enact legislation to require photo identification for casting a ballot in Arkansas and to ban [[abortion]] after twenty weeks of gestation. He was a co-sponsor of both of those measures. Westerman also supported related [[pro-life]] legislation to outlaw abortion whenever fetal heartbeat is detected, to forbid the inclusion of abortion in the state insurance exchange, and to make the death of an unborn child a [[felony]] in certain cases.<ref name=votingrecords/>\n\nOn [[Second Amendment to the United States Constitution|Second Amendment]] issues, Westerman co-sponsored allowing officials of universities and religious institutions to engage in the [[concealed carry]] of firearms. He voted to reduce the application fee for obtaining a concealed carry permit, but the measure was defeated in the House. Westerman  supported the measure which prohibits the governor from regulating firearms during an emergency. He voted for the failed measure to prohibit the closing of schools based on a two-year pupil enrollment analysis. He voted to establish a tiered system of [[lottery]] scholarships. He voted against legislation to make the office of prosecuting attorney in Arkansas [[nonpartisan]], which nevertheless passed sixty-three to twenty-four. He voted to establish a tiered system of [[lottery]] scholarships. He supported the bill, signed by Governor Beebe, to permit the sale of up to five hundred gallons per month of [[pasteurization|unpasteurized]] whole milk directly from the farm to consumers.<ref name=votingrecords>{{cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/candidate/key-votes/119120/bruce-westerman|title=Bruce Westerman\'s Voting Records|publisher=votesmart.org|accessdate=January 12, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Westerman voted for dress codes and the establishment of state standards for biblical instruction in public schools. He voted to prohibit cell phone usage in school zones. He voted to require that state driver\'s license tests be administered only in the [[English language]]. He co-sponsored the Capital Gains Reduction Act and the reduction of taxes on manufacturers\' utilities. He voted against the 2011 congressional [[redistricting]] act.<ref name=votingrecords/>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n*Revenue And Taxation Committee \n**Subcommittee on Sales, Use, Miscellaneous Taxes and Exemptions (Chair)\n*State Agencies And Governmental Affairs Committee\n*Insurance and Commerce Committee<ref>http://www.arkansashouse.org/member/296/bruce-westerman</ref>\n\n==2014 congressional election==\nWesterman won the Republican congressional primary on May 20, 2014, by defeating Tommy Moll 54%-46%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.katv.com/story/12801589/katv-election-results|title=Arkansas Primary Election Results, May 20, 2014|publisher=[[KATV]]|accessdate=May 21, 2014}}</ref> In November, he defeated Democratic nominee [[James Lee Witt]], a former associate of [[U.S. President]] [[Bill Clinton]], 53.7%-42.6%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.realclearpolitics.com/epolls/2014/house/ar/arkansas_4th_district_westerman_vs_witt-5062.html|accessdate=26 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n==114th Congress==\n\n===Committee Assignments===\nIn the 114th Congress, Westerman will serve on the:\n\n*[[House Committee on Natural Resources]] <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brucewesterman.com/westerman_tapped_for_natural_resources_budget_committees|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref>\n*[[House Committee on the Budget]] <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brucewesterman.com/westerman_tapped_for_natural_resources_budget_committees|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref>\n*[[House Committee on Science, Space and Technology]] <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brucewesterman.com/westerman_to_serve_on_house_science_committee|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal bar|Arkansas|American football|Schools|Politics|Conservatism|Baptist}}\n\n*[http://www.brucewesterman.com Campaign Website]\n*[http://votesmart.org/candidate/biography/119120/bruce-westerman#.Ufp7ro1_2uk VoteSmart.org]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box|\nbefore=[[Bill Sample]]\n|title=[[Arkansas House of Representatives|Arkansas State Representative from District 30]]\nBruce Eugene Westerman\n|years=2011&ndash;2013|\nafter=Charles Armstrong}}\n{{succession box|\nbefore=[[Nate Bell]] (moved to District 20)\n|title=[[Arkansas House of Representatives|Arkansas State Representative from District 22]]\nBruce Eugene Westerman\n|years=2013&ndash;2015|\nafter=Missing\n{{succession box|\nbefore=[[Tom Cotton]]\n|title=[[United States House of Representatives|United States Representative]] from [[Arkansas\'s 4th congressional district]]\nBruce Eugene Westerman\n|years=2015&ndash;\n|after=Incumbent}}\n}}\n{{end box}}\n{{Arkansas House of Representatives}}\n{{Persondata <!-- Metadata: see [[Wikipedia:Persondata]]. -->\n| NAME              =Westerman, Bruce\n| ALTERNATIVE NAMES =Bruce Eugene Westerman\n| SHORT DESCRIPTION = American politician\n| DATE OF BIRTH     =November 18, 1967\n| PLACE OF BIRTH    =[[Hot Springs, Arkansas]]\n| DATE OF DEATH     =\n| PLACE OF DEATH    =\n}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Westerman, Bruce}}\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Hot Springs, Arkansas]]\n[[Category: